{"id":"1807.00970","submitter":"Fenner Harper","authors":"Fenner Harper, David Bauer, T. S. Jackson, Rahul Roy","title":"Finite-wavevector Electromagnetic Response in Lattice Quantum Hall\n  Systems","comments":"17 pages, 3 figures. v2: published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 98, 245303 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.98.245303","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In a quantum Hall system, the finite-wavevector Hall conductivity displays an\nintriguing dependence on the Hall viscosity, a coefficient that describes the\nnon-dissipative response of the fluid to a velocity gradient. In this paper, we\npursue this connection in detail for quantum Hall systems on a lattice, noting\nthat the neat continuum relation breaks down and develops corrections due to\nthe broken rotational symmetry. In the process, we introduce a new, quantum\nmechanical derivation of the finite-wavevector Hall conductivity for the\ninteger quantum Hall effect, which allows terms to arbitrary order in the\nwavevector expansion to be calculated straightforwardly. We also develop a\nuniversal formalism for studying quantum Hall physics on a lattice, and find\nthat at weak applied magnetic fields, generic lattice wavefunctions connect\nsmoothly to the Landau levels of the continuum. At moderate field strengths,\nthe lattice corrections can be significant and perturb the wavefunctions,\nenergy levels, and transport properties from their continuum values. Our\napproach allows the finite-field behaviour of a system to be inferred directly\nfrom the zero-field band structure.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Jul 2018 04:04:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Jan 2020 16:31:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-03"}
