{"id":"1807.01036","submitter":"Lorenzo De Angelis","authors":"L. De Angelis, F. Alpeggiani, and L. Kuipers","title":"Spatial bunching of same-charge polarization singularities in\n  two-dimensional random vector waves","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. X 8, 041012 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevX.8.041012","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Topological singularities are ubiquitous in many areas of physics.\nPolarization singularities are locations at which an aspect of the polarization\nellipse of light becomes undetermined or degenerate. At C points the\norientation of the ellipse becomes degenerate and light's electric field vector\ndescribes a perfect circle in time. In 2D slices of 3D random fields the\ndistribution in space of the C points is reminiscent of that of interacting\nparticles. With near-field experiments we show that when light becomes truly\n2D, this has severe consequences for the distribution of C points in space. The\nmost notable change is that the probability of finding two C points with the\nsame topological charge at a vanishing distance is enhanced in a 2D field. This\nis an unusual finding for any system which exhibits topological singularities\nas same-charge repulsion is typically observed. All our experimental findings\nare supported with theory and excellent agreement is found between theory and\nexperiment.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Jul 2018 09:12:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-10-24"}
